@nook_ethereum それは間違い。

イーサリアムはWeb3と言っているだけ。

Web3はイーサリアムしかないとは書いてない。

@nook_ethereum @hirox246 それはあなたの思想であり、私の思想ではありません。

にも関わらず、「それをちゃんと説明すべきなのでは」は意味が分かりません。

前提を満たしていないので、説明すべきだと考えていません。

@nook_ethereum @hirox246 取引所を含めたブロックチェーンのエコシステムを前提としています。そうでないとすると多くの矛盾が生じます。

まずは、何が取引所の役割で、何がブロックチェーン技術の範疇なのかを勉強してください。

これ以上、ご自身の独自理論で非論理的な発言を続けるのであればブロックします。

@nook_ethereum @hirox246 「L1では取引所がハッキングされても、みんなが取引履歴を追って盗難資金を特定することができる」という前提を肯定するのですか？

ハッキング事件の被害者のことを考えてあげてください。

仮にこの前提を肯定するのであっても取引所の存在なしでは語れないし、マネロンの話をするこたになりますよ。

@cmoyall @emschanning @josh_blockchain Me: Christine, can you tell us more about the privacy model in the JPMorgan tokenized debt project?
Christine: Sure, we had forked the public Ethereum- wait, am I describing Quorum to you? This is weird. 

😂 Def the most fun I’ve had on a panel in a long time 😘

@cameronpalmer19 Polygon &lt;&gt; Ethereum
Stacks &lt;&gt; Bitcoin 

Is a good analogy. Technical details etc are different but at a high-level yes.

@0x9fd @mikerwarner There are DEXes built on Stacks itself like @ArkadikoFinance.

It’s not on Ethereum based DEXes, people can wrap STX to list it there.

Decentralized ecosystem so someone might do it. My company focuses on dev tools.

@danprimack Sure they can! A lot of apps built on top are also decentralized protocols.

Ethereum is the smart contract platform (most VCs missed it) but then Uniswap app built on top itself is decentralized.

Some VCs invest in these but compared to web2, drastically reduced control.

@csuwildcat I don’t think (1) or (2) should ever be at the Bitcoin base layer.

If I liked that design then I would’ve started a separate L1 like Ethereum or Solana.

I think that a durable/simple money layer of Bitcoin combined with a layer for expressive contracts is powerful.

@PrestonPysh @adam3us @fluidvoice @Stacks Yep you’re close to the crux of it.

There are alternate designs like Liquid (federated not open) or DLCs/RGB (offline limited smart contracts).

Fully expressive smart contracts like what devs are used to on Ethereum, Avalanche etc on open networks require gas assets.

@BitcoinAsteroid @PrestonPysh @APompliano @FrancisSuarez As much as I like Taproot (it’s great!) we should not confuse it with fully expressive smart contracts.

The type of contracts enables by Taproot are offline contracts which are fairly limited compared to what devs are used to on Ethereum, Solana etc.

Stacks has full contracts.

@ASvanevik Did you know that I was part of the Ethereum genesis distribution?

So been touching it since birth 😉

P.S: My tweet was directed at Bitcoin purists RE some NFT discussions.

@bradmillscan @adam3us I’m a builder and early Bitocoiner; I’ve helped build the best possible system we can to grow the Bitcoin economy w/ smart contracts.

Ethereum and the other L1s will eat your lunch if you stay blind to it.

The $1B sats version is clearly inferior. ETH will burn $5B in one year.

@fuserleer I mostly look at what developers are doing (vs. transaction volumes). 

There is solid data, e.g., stats from GitHub, that shows that developers are increasingly building on new L1s.

Does not mean Ethereum is not growing itself. But “ghost chains” is just false.

@WillPow13 I used quotes for “Ethereum killers” because I don’t like the term.

These are new L1s with novel capabilities and they’re finding use cases for those capabilities.

Of course, some overlap and competition with existing Ethereum.

@SomsenRuben @WinstonLaMoine @PatrickWStanley @ercwl @Stacks How many developers are building on XRP vs Ethereum vs Bitcoin sidechains?

In the end, developers will decide which solutions gain market adoption.

Underestimating Ethereum or others because they have gas assets seems like a blind spot in your thinking.

@SDLerner @lightcoin @RSKsmart @Liquid_BTC @ethereum @Namecoin @Stacks I wouldn’t qualify Stacks or Namecoin to be sidechains. (Ethereum is just a separate network with nothing to do with Bitcoin).

Namecoin was merged mined.

Stacks uses PoX to connect to Bitcoin, different consensus.

@mohits274 Sure but it’s on Ethereum. 

Bitcoin is sovereign money and using it as a reserve asset like gold can be super interesting.

In this way the BTC under reserve never “leaves” the BTC main chain.

@bradmillscan @APompliano @Stacks You can fork the code, remove the token, and see if it works.

Nodes need incentives to maintain the smart contract state and to execute smart contracts. You also can’t put that state in Bitcoin.

Can hate the token and lose smart contracts market to Ethereum OR innovate on BTC.

@santiagoroel I read your thesis as Ethereum + DeFi will be bigger than Bitcoin. Ethereum is also a SoV (hence no need for Bitcoin).

In other words, most of the action will happen on Ethereum, including the SoV use case of Bitcoin.

In my view, Bitcoin clearly wins SoV and can take on DeFi.

@MacBudkowski @alive_eth Ok, let’s get more precise because indeed we are arguing over a shitpost.

Of course network effects are well-defined, even in blockchain. Obviously the marginal user to Ethereum increases its value.

Network effects are used to argue that this chain or that is defensible.

